<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Siberian air crash kills 120: Pilots' chief blames Aeroflot
break-up for poor safety
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LEYLA BOULTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MOSCOW
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The head of Russia's pilots' union called for 'an end to the mess' in the
domestic airline industry after 120 people died yesterday in the country's
worst air crash for a decade.
A Tupolev-154 crashed in Siberian farmland just after taking off from
Irkutsk, near Lake Baikal, for a five-hour flight to Moscow. All 120 crew
and passengers, including 16 foreigners, were killed after the engines
failed and the aircraft caught fire in mid-air. Nine of the 16 foreigners
who died were German, and four Chinese.
Mr Alfred Malinovski, head of the pilots' union, said in an interview with
the Financial Times that the crash was part of a 'harvest of accidents
which, to a significant degree, is being reaped because of the shocks
suffered by the aviation industry'.
He claimed that, with the break-up of Aeroflot into 160 local carriers such
as Baikal Air, whose aircraft crashed yesterday, safety checks had been
weakened and pilots had little control over the over-loading of aircraft
with cargo, fuel and passengers.
'The industry is in a fearful state. Not enough money is spent on repairs,
and enforcing safety regulations. Pilots have to travel with bags of cash to
pay for fuel and tend to load as much fuel wherever they are because prices
are so unpredictable.
'Crudely speaking, things are a mess.'
At its year-end press conference, the Russian Transport Ministry reported
that fatal accidents on Russian airlines had dropped to 10 last year from 24
in 1992.
Mr Malinovski added that ground staff and crew were vulnerable to bribes and
threats to take on extra cargo.
The threats come particularly from small traders who criss-cross the country
reselling goods and transporting them on passenger tickets.
While some of the units that have emerged from the break-up of Aeroflot and
some of the many new airlines have improved services, domestic travel within
the former Soviet Union remains dismal.
</TEXT>
