<HEADLINE>
FT  04 JAN 94 / Media review aims to boost UK ownership overseas
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A wide-ranging review of UK cross-media ownership designed to encourage
British companies to take advantage of opportunities in international media
markets was announced by the government yesterday.
It is likely that further deregulation of broadcasting ownership rules could
follow, allowing a larger role for newspaper publishers in television
ownership, when the inter-departmental review ends in about six months.
Mr Peter Brooke, the national heritage secretary, who promised a wider
review in November when he announced proposals to allow one company to own
two ITV licences, said he wanted to see UK participation 'in an enormously
expanding market'.
The review comes against a background of rapid changes in the industry and
growing internationalisation of media ownership.
Newspaper proprietors, including Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, and
Associated Newspapers, owner of the Daily Mail, have been lobbying hard to
remove the rules which at present prevent them holding more than a 20 per
cent stake in either commercial television or radio stations.
Mr Frank Barlow, managing director of Pearson, said yesterday: 'Assuming it
leads to a relaxation, it is something we would very much welcome. It is a
natural extension of newspaper publishing.'
The review will bring together officials from the National Heritage
Department, the Department of Trade and Industry and the Downing Street
policy unit. After it is complete a further round of ministerial meetings is
expected, suggesting that policy changes are unlikely before the autumn.
'It is intended to examine things looked at at the time of the Broadcasting
Act 1990, but also at the variety of relationships between newspapers, TV
companies, radio stations and the press,' said Mr Brooke.
Ms Marjorie Mowlam, Labour's national heritage spokeswoman, generally
welcomed the announcement, but wondered whether newspapers would be allowed
greater participation in television ownership in return for accepting value
added tax on newspapers in the next Budget.
Mr Brooke said in an interview on BBC Radio 4's World at One programme that
the review would broaden out to look at 'the way the world is developing
much more widely'. This could include everything from television programmes
to films, videos, music, computer games, home shopping and information of
all kinds.
He was determined however to maintain the UK's domestic production base
because, he said, people liked watching things produced in their own country
'through their own national filter'.
It was also important to maintain a plurality of views and a diversity of
choice in broadcasting, said Mr Brooke.
</TEXT>
