<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JAN 94 / Books: Rounding up the villains in a big-budget disaster - A
look at the making of Baron Munchausen
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIGEL ANDREWS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LOSING THE LIGHT
by Andrew Yule
Applause Pounds 12.99 240 pages
The production history of Terry Gilliam's The Adventures of Baron Munchausen
demonstrates one of the oldest truths of cinema: that big-budget film-making
is the Creation story in reverse.
Give God six days to make the world and he will create order from chaos.
Give a director 60 days to make a film - and almost as many million dollars
 -and chaos will be conjured unfailingly from a carefully costed,
theoretically foolproof gleam of inspiration.
Andrew Yule's book, funny and informative, is the appalling made real. He
never went near the set during the film's making but has been rounding up
the suspects ever since: including director Terry Gilliam, one-time Monty
Python cartoonist turned film director; German producer Thomas Schuhly,
ex-collaborator with Fassbinder and Fellini; and a mixture of international
stars and technicians (Italian designers, Hollywood comedians).
Baron Munchausen began as a Dollars 20m extravaganza, funded by Columbia on
a pick-up basis and to be made in Italy and Spain by a director with a track
record in low-budget inventiveness (The Time Bandits, Brazil).
Then, like Heaven's Gate and Topsy, it just growed. Yule's book begins with
teasing innocence. What could be brighter and safer than signing up a great
modern movie fantasist (Gilliam) to remake a great bygone movie fantasy?
The old Baron Munchhausen, made in 1943, was a living picture-book. Stuffed
with trips to the moon, headless giants and heroes riding cannonballs, it
was one of the few good things to come out of Germany during the Hitler
years.
The 1989-model Munchausen, when it came out, sank without a ripple at the
box office. But long before that it was measuring up for disaster.
The budget reached Dollars 40-50m (ledgers always become blurry after a
movie's initial cost has doubled), and the shooting schedule spun out from
weeks to months as if Scheherezade were in charge of production management.
In such stories there has to be a villain and Andrew Yule's is Schuhly. He
is Losing The Light's dark angel: a vainglorious egomaniac (so alleged) who
spent more time pumping his muscles at the gym or basking in the lights at
Press briefings than he did in making sure sets were built, costs were
controlled and promised international stars (Marlon Brando, Sean Connery)
turned up for work.
Eric Idle, one of the film's performers, comments: 'He told us that what you
need for film-making is balls. And that's all he ever talked - balls.'
In the other corner, we have Mr Gilliam. Gilliam - it is the book's major
failing - is presented with an almost unblotted copybook.
His one mild foible seems to be a lovable absent-mindedness: note the day he
ordered his age-hopping hero (John Neville) to get into Munchausen's
80-year-old guise (four hours in the make-up room) and then realised that
the day's shooting called for a 65-year-old Baron. Neville, already seething
at a schedule that threatened to eat into his next Stratford Ontario season,
duly exploded.
Elsewhere, Yule acts less like Gilliam's portraitist than his defence
counsel. But surely a director must have prime responsibility for the
unravelling disciplines on a movie set - especially if he conceived the
movie and proclaimed its financial viability to begin with.
Instead, Losing The Light finds fault with other parties, some of the
finger-pointing no doubt justified: with Rome's Cinecitta Studios for its
old-fashioned work methods; with Film Finance, the completion bond company,
for insisting on niggardly and false economies; and with the world of
international bacteria for spreading plagues around the cast both animal and
human - African horse fever, dogs struck by liver ailments, actors struck
down by everything available.
The book, whatever the justice of its apportioning of praise and blame, has
its comic momentum horribly correct: once things start to go wrong on a big
movie, they don't stop.
It makes cinema unique as an art: a form of Promethean presumption that
results either in gorgeous artistic conflagrations or in entire creative
enterprises having their innards pecked out. Losing The Light is a book to
learn from, smile at and shudder over.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P2731 Book Publishing.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>TECH  Products &amp; Product use.
</TP>
