<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JAN 94 / Regional divide narrows
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The recession has narrowed the north-south divide, figures from the Central
Statistical Office showed yesterday.
Gross domestic product per head in south-east England slipped back while
that in Scotland, Northern Ireland and the north moved forward. But an
east-west divide opened up with East Anglia seeing the biggest rise and
north-west England the steepest fall.
Regional figures for 1992 showed that while GDP in Greater London was down
almost 2 per cent on 1991, Scotland, Northern Ireland and the north saw
their second successive relative increase. Total GDP in 1992 was Pounds
514bn, up 4 per cent on 1991. More than a third was accounted for by the
south-east, with Greater London alone responsible for 14.7 per cent.
