<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JAN 94 / Briefcase, Q&amp;A: Investment bonds
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Could you clarify the following points about single premium investment
bonds?
1. In calculating the gain referred-to in section 547(1) of the Income and
Corporation Taxes Act 1988, can the cost of a bond be increased in
accordance with the retail prices index (ie, in the way that the cost of an
asset subject to capital gains tax may be increased)?
2. Is the tax due subject to 'top-slicing' relief and is what I say in (a)
and (b) below correct?
For example, suppose that in 1992-93 John Smith cashed a bond he had held
for 17 policy years and realised a profit of Pounds 17,000. Apart from this
Pounds 17,000, he had taxable income of Pounds 15,000.
(a) With top-slicing relief, his taxable income would be increased by Pounds
1,000 to Pounds 16,000; thus, he would pay no tax on the profit of Pounds
17,000.
(b) Without top-slicing relief, his taxable income would be increased to
Pounds 32,000. He would then pay tax at 15 per cent on Pounds 8,300 of this
(viz, Pounds 1,245).
3. What precisely is meant by indexation losses?
1. No.
2. Yes, for the purpose of giving relief from the 15 per cent surcharge for
potential higher-rate taxpayers, but not for relief from the 12 1/2 per cent
age surcharge for basic-rate taxpayers over 64 (at the beginning of the tax
year); and, yes, your example is right.
3. If an asset within the scope of CGT (and not specifically denied the
benefit of indexation relief) was sold before Budget day for the same amount
as it cost originally (after April 5 1982), there will be an allowable loss
equal to indexation relief on the cost for the period of ownership: such an
allowable loss is generally called an indexation loss (ie, a loss which
simply represents indexation relief).
No legal responsibility can be accepted by the Financial Times for the
answers given in these columns. All enquiries will be answered by post as
soon as possible.
</TEXT>
