<HEADLINE>
FT  01 JAN 94 / Arts: Musical farce may sharpen the batons - Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MAX LOPPERT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Any bets on the fate of the Arts Council of Great Britain in 1994? The Great
London Orchestra Farce came to an end in the middle of last month, and
mockery and abuse then rained down on the whole organisation  - accompanied
by more than one public call for it to be wound up altogether, and replaced
by a line of direct government funding of the arts.
The hilarious yet heartbreaking saga of administrative tomfoolery that led
to the outcry may be briefly summarised as follows: an independent team set
up by the musical panel of the Arts Council to decide, by means of a 'beauty
contest' which one of three London orchestras would become a super-orchestra
and, in counterbalance, which other two would lose their grant; a huge
outcry by supporters of all three orchestras elicited by the beauty contest;
a concluding judgment by the independent team then completely ignored by the
Council; a final decision on orchestral funding for 1994-95 amounting to a
comprehensive fudge of the whole issue.
The questions which arise out of the settling dust and all the merriment at
the Council's expense are the following: does a body that in the last few
years has shown both an inability to support all its clients effectively,
and a propensity to turn against some of those clients on what has often
looked like the merest whim - does such a body deserve to exist any longer?
There is no predicting with confidence either its survival or
disintegration. But, in curious and rather satisfyingly unexpected fashion,
one side-effect of the 'beauty contest' seems to have been a greatly
increased sense of artistic urgency among the London orchestras recently
under scrutiny - a sense of sharpened concern to raise the standard and
'interest-quotient' of both programmes and roster of conductors and
soloists.
The Philharmonia, with an exceptionally interesting programme of
early-evening contemporary-music concerts already in its second year of
existence, seems to have woken up the most. The London Philharmonic, though
its recent welcoming-on-board of Harrison Birtwistle and Roger Norrington
had the look of a desperate face-saving exercise, now looks set to follow
suit. (Neither of those orchestras will really gain full credibility,
however, until the question-marks hanging over their far-from-infallible
Chief Conductors are resolved - in the case of the Philharmonia's Giuseppe
Sinopoli, the naming of a successor, and in that of the LPO's Franz
Welser-Most, greater evidence of artistic maturity than he has so far
shown.)
The Royal Philharmonic, least-encouraged of the trio, has come out of the
experience with dignity and new sponsorship from Classic FM; its seeking-out
of a 'National Orchestra' identity, and its exciting new links forged with
the Kirov Opera (as witnessed in the splendid concert performance of
Tchaikovksy's opera Iolanta early last month), are two clear tokens of new
vigour there too. And, as everyone has commented, the London Symphony, safe
in its Barbican Hall home, goes from strength to strength: the appointment
of Colin Davis as Chief Conductor (from 1995) has already cast a glow over
all its activities.
So could 1994 be a boom period for London orchestral concerts? Here again,
easy, surefire predictions are not on offer. As my colleague Antony
Thorncroft suggested a few Saturdays ago, the idea of the London
super-orchestra may well come back from the dead in a few years time. And
the basically shaky financial condition of the three beauty-contestant
orchestras should not be forgotten.
But I shall not be at all surprised if, for some while at least through
1994, one result of the London orchestral brouhaha is a pleasingly ironic
one: a newly vital, uncomplacent London orchestral scene.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P792  Producers, Orchestras, Entertainers.
    P8699 Membership Organizations, NEC.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>CMMT  Comment &amp; Analysis.
</TP>
