FT  01 JAN 94 / Sudan told to halt expulsion
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The British government yesterday gave Sudan until next Tuesday to reverse
its decision to expel Mr Peter Streams, the British ambassador to Khartoum.
Mr Abdurrahman Bakhit, Sudanese charge d'affaires in the UK, was called to
the Foreign Office yesterday and told that the expulsion should be withdrawn
if Sudan valued its relationship with Britain. The expulsion was apparently
provoked by a proposed visit to rebel-held areas in southern Sudan by Dr
George Carey, archbishop of Canterbury.
The Foreign Office said the Sudanese government had been told of Britain's
'profound dissatisfaction and regret' at the expulsion order.
The Foreign Office did not say what measures would be taken if Sudan did not
comply.
